-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - April 11
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Thu Apr 10, 2014 09:49PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, April 11 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- The kidnappers who snatched a Chinese tourist from a Malaysian holiday resort have demanded a ransom of HK$87 million ($11.2 million). Malaysian Home Minister Ahmad Zahid Hamidi said they received a note from the kidnappers demanding a ransom.  (http://link.reuters.com/bar48v) -- China must not be too hasty in opening up its capital account before solving serious domestic problems, including a housing bubble and inefficient allocation of resources, a prominent economist said. (http://link.reuters.com/kar48v) -- Pan-democrats have managed to secure an exclusive meeting with central government officials in Shanghai - and Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying won't be there. Legislative Council president Jasper Tsang Yok-sing has confirmed that the pan-democrats will have a two-hour reform discussion with the officials on Sunday. (http://link.reuters.com/mar48v)  THE STANDARD -- A district court convicted three mainland businessmen involved in using false financial documents with a face value of HK$90 billion ($11.61 billion) in dealing with the failed Hong Kong Mercantile Exchange. (http://link.reuters.com/qar48v) -- The family of Macau casino magnate Stanley Ho may buy a stake in a Taiwan life insurance business worth up to NT$9 billion ($287.63 million). Sources said Taiwan developer Long Bon International will sell a 19 percent stake in Taiwan Life Insurance to Chanceton Financial Group <8020.HK>, controlled by Ho's daughter, for NT$2.68 billion. (http://link.reuters.com/rar48v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd <0688.HK> said it  generated 10.81 billion yuan ($1.74 billion) from sales of flats in March, up 19 percent from the previous month but down 26 percent as compared to the same period a year ago. -- China Financial Services Holdings Ltd <0605.HK> said it planned to sell 300 million shares at HK$0.55 each in a share placement, raising HK$162.7 million ($20.99 million)for general working capital.  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- CITIC Pacific <0267.HK> aims to make an announcement on April 16 detailing CITIC Group Corp's [CITIC.UL] asset injection into the Hong Kong-listed firm, which is pending regulatory approval, said executive chairman Chang Zhenming.MING PAO DAILY NEWS  -- Kam Tin South and Pat Heung in New Territories in Hong Kong will be turned into a new town with 33,701 flats to be built under a proposal put forward by the city's planning department, providing housing for 92,800 people.